====================================================================
üìå SQL BASIC COMMANDS (USE, SELECT, DESCRIBE, ALIAS) ‚Äî NOTES + EXAMPLES
====================================================================

SQL (Structured Query Language) is used to store, retrieve, update,
and manage data in relational databases.

Below are the MOST IMPORTANT basic SQL commands used in MySQL.

====================================================================

# 1Ô∏è‚É£ USE DATABASE
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Used to select/activate a database so that you can perform operations
on its tables.

SYNTAX:
    USE database_name;
====================================================================
*/

USE world;       -- selecting the 'world' database


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ SHOW DATABASES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Shows a list of all databases stored in the MySQL server.
====================================================================
*/

SHOW DATABASES;


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ CHECK CURRENT DATABASE
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
MySQL function to see which database is currently selected.
====================================================================
*/

SELECT DATABASE();


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ SHOW TABLES
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
Displays all tables present inside the currently selected database.
====================================================================
*/

SHOW TABLES;


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 5Ô∏è‚É£ DESCRIBE TABLE
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
`DESCRIBE table_name;` shows the structure of a table:
‚úî Columns  
‚úî Datatypes  
‚úî NULL/NOT NULL  
‚úî Keys  
‚úî Defaults  

====================================================================
*/

DESCRIBE city;     -- shows structure of the 'city' table


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 6Ô∏è‚É£ SELECT ALL DATA
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
SELECT * retrieves all columns from the table.
====================================================================
*/

SELECT * FROM city;    -- fetch complete data


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 7Ô∏è‚É£ SELECT SPECIFIC COLUMNS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Choose only required columns instead of fetching full table.
====================================================================
*/

SELECT population, name, district FROM city;

SELECT name, population
FROM city;


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 8Ô∏è‚É£ USING EXPRESSIONS IN SELECT
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
You can perform calculations directly inside SELECT.
====================================================================
*/

SELECT 
    name, 
    population, 
    population + 10 AS increased_population 
FROM city;


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# 9Ô∏è‚É£ MULTILINE SELECT STATEMENTS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
You can break long SELECT queries into multiple lines for readability.
====================================================================
*/

SELECT 
    name,
    population,
    countrycode,
    population
FROM city;


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
# üîü ALIAS (AS) ‚Äî NICKNAME FOR COLUMNS
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Aliasing renames a column or table temporarily for readability.

`AS` ‚Üí used to give custom names.

====================================================================
*/

SELECT *, 
       population * 2 AS new_population
FROM country;

-- new_population is an alias


--------------------------------------------------------------------
====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================
‚úî USE database_name   ‚Üí activate a database  
‚úî SHOW DATABASES      ‚Üí list all available databases  
‚úî SELECT DATABASE()   ‚Üí check selected DB  
‚úî SHOW TABLES         ‚Üí list tables inside DB  
‚úî DESCRIBE table      ‚Üí show table structure  
‚úî SELECT *            ‚Üí select all columns  
‚úî SELECT column1,...  ‚Üí select specific columns  
‚úî Aliases (AS)        ‚Üí rename columns  
‚úî SQL is not case-sensitive ‚Üí but UPPERCASE keywords recommended  

END OF NOTES.
====================================================================
